1DraftPicks}}\n{{Cincinnati Bengals roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, A. J.}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bengals players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Under Armour All-American football players]]\n[[Category:People from Summerville, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=A.J. Green\n|image=Adriel_Jeremiah_Green.jpg\n|image_size=225px\n|alt=A.J Green\n|caption=Green in 2013\n|current_team=Cincinnati Bengals <!-- Note: Set to be a free agent. Do not change until March 18, 2020 at 4:00 P.M. EST. -->\n|number=18\n|position=[[Wide receiver]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1988|7|31|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Summerville, South Carolina]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs=210\n|high_school=[[Summerville High School|Summerville]]<br />([[Summerville, South Carolina]])\n|college=[[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n|draftyear=2011\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=4\n|pastteams=\n*[[Cincinnati Bengals]] ({{NFL Year|2011}}\u2013present)\n|status= Franchise tag\n|highlights=\n* 7\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2012 Pro Bowl|2011]]\u2013[[2018 Pro Bowl|2017]])\n* 3\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2012 All-Pro Team|2012]], [[2013 All-Pro Team|2013]], [[2015 All-Pro Team|2015]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] (2011)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-American]] ([[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009]], [[2010 College Football All-America Team|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2008 All-SEC football team|2008]], [[2009 All-SEC football team|2009]])\n* Second-team All-SEC ([[2010 All-SEC football team|2010]])\n* [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards|SEC Freshman of the Year]] (2008)\n*  ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[2007 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2007]])\n|statleague=NFL\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1=602\n|statlabel2=[[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue2=8,907\n|statlabel3=[[Average|Receiving average]]\n|statvalue3=14.8\n|statlabel4=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue4=63\n|nfl=GRE034604\n}}\n{{for|the basketball player|AJ Green (basketball)}}\n'''Adriel Jeremiah''' \"'''A.J.'''\" '''Green''' (born July 31, 1988) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Georgia]] for the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]], and was drafted by the Bengals fourth overall in the [[2011 NFL Draft]].\n\nIn his first season with the Bengals, Green made the [[2012 Pro Bowl]], the first rookie receiver to make a Pro Bowl appearance in eight years; Green has since gone on to appear in seven total Pro Bowls in his career. From 2011 to 2013, Green caught more passes (260) than any other player in NFL history during their first three seasons, though this record was later broken by [[Jarvis Landry]]. He has had six seasons with 1,000 or more receiving yards.\n\n== Early life ==\nA. J. Green is the son of Woodrow and Dora Green; Woodrow was a steel worker and truck driver and Dora, a clerk at a [[Wal-Mart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlineathens.com/stories/061707/football_20070617066.shtml|title=Highly talented wide receiver ready to don red and black - Online Athens|access-date=December 9, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208193037/http://onlineathens.com/stories/061707/football_20070617066.shtml|archive-date=February 8, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/29/sports/football/bengals-aj-green-is-fierce-playmaker-with-quiet-approach.html|title=A Fierce Playmaker Who Shrugs Off Praise|date=December 29, 2012|work=The New York Times}}</ref> When A. J. was age 4, his only sibling, older brother Avionce, died in a car wreck on the way to a school carnival; the wreck also left their aunt paralyzed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/preview10/columns/story?id=5470093&columnist=forde_pat |title=Forde: Green pastures |last=Forde |first=Pat |date=August 17, 2010 |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Green was on his elementary school's [[juggling]] team, telling ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' that he learned to juggle as early as second grade. Green said he could juggle as many as four items at once, and that the ability helped the development of his hand-eye coordination.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-ga-star-turns-circus-skills-into-circus-catches-2010aug26-story.html |title=Ga. star turns circus skills into circus catches |last=Newberry |first=Paul |work=sandiegouniontribune.com |access-date=April 2, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== High school career ==\nGreen attended [[Summerville High School]], where he was a three-sport athlete in [[high school football|football]], basketball, and track.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://abcnews4.com/archive/nfl-standout-aj-green |title=NFL standout A.J. Green returns home |last=Bainum |first=Stefanie |work=WCIV |access-date=April 2, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> He played as a [[wide receiver]] for the Summerville Green Wave [[high school football]] team, under coach [[John McKissick]]. He was widely considered to be one of the top national football prospects of the Class of 2008, and was listed #1 by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/08/04/top10.football08/index.html |title=Green headlines top 10 football players in Class of '08 |last=Mahoney |first=Jon |date=August 4, 2006 |website=Sports Illustrated |access-date=April 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author =Jon Mahoney |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/highschool/12/21/whos.next/index.html |title=Who's Got Next? |work=Sports Illustrated |date=December 22, 2006 |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> Green earned All-State honors four times and was the only junior nominated to the 2006 ''[[USA Today]]'' All-American first team following 75 receptions for 1,422 yards and 16 touchdowns during his sophomore season. Green was also selected as a member of the [[Rivals.com]] Junior All-America team based on those stats.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=638213 |title=Junior All-America Team |last=Shurburtt |first=JC |publisher=Rivals.com |access-date=April 1, 2012}}</ref> As a freshman, he had 57 receptions for 1,217 yards and eight touchdowns. As a sophomore, he had 60 catches for 1,203 yards and 14 touchdowns.\n\nGreen's 5,373 career receiving yards rank second in the all-time career receiving records of the National Federation of High Schools. His 279 career receptions rank fourth.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Roger |url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/content/shared-blogs/ajc/cfbrecruit/entries/2008/02/06/aj_green_signs.html |title=Coach: No receiver better than A.J. Green |publisher=Ajc.com |date=February 6, 2008 |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> In June 2006, Green was profiled by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' as part of its \u201cWhere Will They Be?\u201d stories documenting athletes with the potential of becoming a future great, alongside [[Peter Uihlein]], [[John Tavares (ice hockey)|John Tavares]], [[Tyreke Evans]], [[Elena Delle Donne]], and others.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/magazine/06/26/where.will.they.be0703/1.html |title=Where Will They Be? |work=SI.com |date=June 26, 2006 }}</ref> ''Sports Illustrated'' compared him to the then-[[Oakland Raiders]] wideout [[Randy Moss]] and predicted Green will be in the [[NFL]] by 2011. Green was also on the school's [[track & field]] team, where he competed as a long jumper (top-jump of 19&nbsp;ft 6 in) and triple jumper (40&nbsp;ft 0 in).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/a-j-green-3390/|title=A.J. Green - Georgia - Bengals WR|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023161722/https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/a-j-green-3390/|archivedate=October 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rivals.com]]'' ranked Green as their No. 9 prospect for the high school class of 2008, while ''[[Scout.com]]'' named Green their No. 10 prospect nationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rivals100.rivals.com/viewrank.asp?SID=880&Year=2008&ra_key=1803 |title=2008 Rivals.com Top 100 |publisher=Rivals100.rivals.com |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=9&c=4&pid=88&yr=2008 |title=2008 Scout.com Football Hot 100 |publisher=Recruiting.scout.com |date=January 4, 2012 |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> He participated in the [[Under Armour All-America Game]].\n\nGreen was also on the Summerville High [[basketball#High school basketball|high school basketball]] team that claimed the 2007\u20132008 South Carolina state championship in a championship game against [[Spartanburg High School|Spartanburg (S.C.) High]].<ref name=\"Basketball\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/mark-bradley-blog/2009/08/10/georgias-aj-green-too-bad-he-only-plays-one-sport/|title=Georgia's A.J. Green: Too bad he only plays one sport|last=Bradley|first=Mark|date=August 10, 2009|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=March 24, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111226143443/http://blogs.ajc.com/mark-bradley-blog/2009/08/10/georgias-aj-green-too-bad-he-only-plays-one-sport/|archivedate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> The game was played in memory of their fallen assistant coach, Captain Louis Mulkey of the Charleston Fire Department in South Carolina, who died responding to a [[Charleston Sofa Super Store fire|fire with eight other firefighters]] on June 18, 2007.<ref name=\"Mulkey\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/preview10/columns/story?columnist=forde_pat&id=5470093|title=A.J. Green relies on lessons learned|last=Forde|first=Pat|date=August 17, 2010|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== College career ==\nGreen verbally committed to attend the [[University of Georgia]] in October 2006,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/recruiting/football/southeast/2006-10-10-southeast.htm |title=Georgia lands top wide receiver |last=Shurburtt |first=JC |date=October 10, 2006 |website=USA Today |access-date=April 1, 2012}}</ref> and made his commitment official by signing a letter of intent to play at Georgia on February 6, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Roger |url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/content/shared-blogs/ajc/cfbrecruit/entries/2008/02/06/aj_green_signs.html |title=A.J. Green Signs with UGA |publisher=Ajc.com |date=February 6, 2008 |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref>  He played for coach [[Mark Richt]]'s [[Georgia Bulldogs football]] team from 2008 to 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/aj-green-1.html |title=A.J. Green College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008 season ===\nGreen had a solid freshman season with the Georgia Bulldogs in [[2008 Georgia Bulldogs football team|2008]]. In the fourth game of his college career, against [[2008 Arizona State Sun Devils football team|Arizona State]], Green had eight catches for 159 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-09-20-arizona-state.html |title=Georgia at Arizona State Box Score, September 20, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> For this, he was named [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_article_id=11552&url_subchannel_id=&change_well_id=2 |title=2008 Week 4 SEC Players of the Week |publisher=Secsports.com |accessdate=April 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927022023/http://www.secsports.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=2&url_subchannel_id=&url_article_id=11552&change_well_id=2 |archivedate=September 27, 2008 }}</ref>\nHe finished the 2008 season with 56 catches for 963 yards and eight touchdowns, all [[University of Georgia|Georgia]] freshman school records.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/aj-green-1/gamelog/2008/ |title=A.J. Green 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He also led the SEC in receiving yards, with the third-highest total in [[University of Georgia|UGA]] school history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/conferences/sec/2008-leaders.html |title=2008 Southeastern Conference Leaders |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He was named second-team All-SEC and Freshman of the Year by the SEC coaches, and was named to the Associated Press All-SEC first team.\n\n=== 2009 season ===\nGreen ended the [[2009 Georgia Bulldogs football team|2009]] regular season with 47 catches for 751 yards and six touchdowns, despite being injured the last three games of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/aj-green-1/gamelog/2009/ |title=A.J. Green 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He returned from injury for the [[2009 Independence Bowl]], December 28, 2009 in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]] where he made six catches totaling 57 yards against the [[2009 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M Aggies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=293620061 |title=ESPN Game Log |publisher=ESPN |date=December 28, 2009 |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-12-28-georgia.html |title=Independence Bowl - Texas A&M vs Georgia Box Score, December 28, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> Among other awards, Green was elected All-SEC First Team by Associated Press, SEC Coaches, ESPN, [[Phil Steele]], and ''[[Sporting News]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=A.J. Green|url=http://www.georgiadogs.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/aj_green_647145.html|website=georgiadogs.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010 season ===\nGreen was suspended for the first four games of the [[2010 Georgia Bulldogs football team|2010 regular season]] after he admitted to selling his 2009 Independence Bowl Jersey for $1,000 to former [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]] defensive back Chris Hawkins, who the NCAA described as an agent or someone who markets amateur athletes.<ref name=Suspension>{{cite news|title=NCAA benches Georgia's A.J. Green|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5547721|accessdate=March 22, 2011|newspaper=ESPN|date=September 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=ChrisHawkins>{{cite news|last=Stevens|first=Alexis|title=A.J. Green jersey buyer facing drug charges|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/uga/a-j-green-jersey-615494.html|accessdate=March 22, 2011|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal Constitution|date=September 16, 2010}}</ref> As part of his punishment, he was required to repay $1,000 to a charity.<ref name=Suspension/> Despite missing the first four games, Green finished the 2010 season with a team-high 57 catches for 848 yards and nine touchdowns.<ref name=Draft>{{cite news|last=Newberry|first=Paul|title=Georgia WR A.J. Green declares for NFL draft|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/jan/9/georgia-wr-aj-green-declares-for-nfl-draft/|accessdate=March 22, 2011|date=January 9, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110214093822/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/jan/9/georgia-wr-aj-green-declares-for-nfl-draft/| archivedate= February 14, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/aj-green-1/gamelog/2010/ |title=A.J. Green 2010 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/georgia/2010.html |title=2010 Georgia Bulldogs Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2011, Green officially declared for the [[2011 NFL Draft]].<ref name=Draft/>  He finished his three seasons at the [[University of Georgia]] with 166 receptions for 2,619 yards and 23 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/aj-green-1.html |title=A.J. Green College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Georgia Bulldogs |color=white}}\" |A. J. Green !!colspan=3| Receiving\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP !! Rec !! Yards !! TDs\n|-\n| [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] || [[2008 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] || 13 || 56 || 963 || 8\n|-\n| [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] || [[2009 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]|| 10 || 53 || 808 || 6\n|-\n| [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]] || [[2010 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]|| 9 || 57 || 848 || 9\n|- style=\"background:#555; font-weight:bold; color:white;\"\n| colspan=2 | College Totals || 32 || 166 || 2,619 || 23\n|}\n\n''Source:''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/aj-green-1.html|title=A.J. Green College Stats - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3 {{Fraction|5|8}}\n|       weight = 211\n|         dash = 4.50\n|    ten split = 1.56\n| twenty split = 2.63\n|      shuttle = 4.21\n|   cone drill = 6.91\n|     vertical = 34\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 6\n|        bench = 18\n|    wonderlic =\n|     arm span = 34\u215c\n|    hand span = 9 1/4\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/a.j.-green?id=2495450 |title=AJ Green Combine Profile |work=NFL.com |accessdate=December 9, 2014 }}.</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:AJ Green.jpg|upright|thumb|A.J. Green in 2011.]]\n\nGreen was selected in the first round with the fourth overall pick in the [[2011 NFL Draft]] by the [[Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/draft.htm |title=2011 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> On July 28, 2011, Green agreed to a four-year contract with the Cincinnati Bengals worth $19.6 million. After signing with the Cincinnati Bengals, Green became a member of [[School of the Legends]] (SOTL) in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110603005764/en/Veteran-Running-Backs-Offer-Rookies-Advice-Exclusive |title=Veteran Running Backs Offer Rookies Advice in Exclusive School of the Legends Interview |last=Renschler |first=Lauren |date=June 3, 2011 |website=Business Wire |access-date=December 6, 2011}}</ref> Green was featured in the 2011 NFLPA Rookie Debut \"One Team\" Celebration which streamed live on [[YouTube]] from New York City's Cipriani Wall Street. The event was produced by SOTL, a licensed partner of the [[NFLPA]], and employed YouTube's live streaming platform.<ref>{{cite web|title=A.J. Green NFL Players Association Rookie Debut 'One Team Celebration' Held...|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/photo/aj-green-nfl-players-association-rookie-debut-one-team-celebration_5646376|work=Contactmusic.com|publisher=Contactmusic.com Ltd.|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011 season ===\nGreen's first NFL reception was a 41-yard touchdown catch against the [[2011 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109110cle.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Cleveland Browns - September 11th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> By the end of his rookie season, Green recorded four 100-yard games and led all NFL rookies in receptions and receiving yards, catching 65 passes for 1,057 yards in 15 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00/gamelog/2011/ |title=A.J. Green 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> His seven touchdown receptions was second among rookies \u2013 one behind [[Julio Jones]] of the [[2011 Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta Falcons]]. On December 18, 2011, Green and fellow rookie quarterback [[Andy Dalton (American football)|Andy Dalton]] surpassed the all-time NFL record for yards and receptions by a rookie quarterback/receiver tandem.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reedy |first=Joe |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20120115/SPORTS/301150070/Bengals-rookie-duo-set-encore |title=Bengals-rookie-duo-set-encore |work=The Courier-Journal |date=January 15, 2012 |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref>  One week later on December 24, 2011, Green's 1,031 yards surpassed [[Cris Collinsworth]]'s franchise record of 1,009 yards set in 1981 for most receiving yards by a rookie. Collinsworth still holds the franchise record for most receptions by a rookie with 67.<ref name=\"rookie record\">{{cite news|url=http://megasportsnews.com/?p=25527|title=Bengals WR Green passes Collinsworth's rookie receiving yardage record|last=Mason|first=Stuart|date=December 25, 2011|publisher=Mega Sports News|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bengals.com/news/article-1/Bengals-flip-Cards-23-16/662b3472-5ff3-483c-b025-014e3b737df1|title=Bengals flip Cards, 23\u201316|date=December 24, 2011|publisher=Bengals.com|accessdate=January 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109022530/http://www.bengals.com/news/article-1/Bengals-flip-Cards-23-16/662b3472-5ff3-483c-b025-014e3b737df1|archive-date=January 9, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 season ===\nIn Week 3 of the 2012 regular season, Green caught nine passes for a career-high 183 yards in a 38-31 win over the [[2012 Washington Redskins|Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209230was.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Washington Redskins - September 23rd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> In Week 9, he caught a 56-yard touchdown against the [[2012 New York Giants|New York Giants]] extending his touchdown streak to eight consecutive games, the longest in the NFL by a receiver and second-longest overall.<ref>{{cite web|title=A.J. Green|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/players/24791/news|work=NFL - Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211110cin.htm |title=New York Giants at Cincinnati Bengals - November 11th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He extended the streak to nine following a four-yard touchdown against the [[2012 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in week 11.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201211180kan.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Kansas City Chiefs - November 18th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> On December 23, 2012, Green recorded his first career lost fumble against the [[2012 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], but he finished the game with 10 receptions for 116 yards, including a 21-yard reception that set up the game-winning field goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212230pit.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Pittsburgh Steelers - December 23rd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> Green gained over 100 receiving yards in five different games and was selected to his second Pro Bowl in his second year in the league.<ref>{{cite web|title=A.J. Green Game By Game Stats and Performance|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/13983/aj-green|work=ESPN|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref>  He finished the season with 97 receptions for 1,350 yards and 11 touchdowns. In the Bengals' [[2012\u201313 NFL playoffs#AFC: Houston Texans 19, Cincinnati Bengals 13|Wild Card Round]] loss to the [[2012 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he was the team's leading receiver with five receptions for 80 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301050htx.htm |title=Wild Card - Cincinnati Bengals at Houston Texans - January 5th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2013 Pro Bowl]], he had 119 yards and three touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/cincinnati-bengals/0ap2000000131561/2013-Pro-Bowl-A-J-Green-highlights|title=2013 Pro Bowl: Cincinnati Bengals wide receiver A.J. Green highlights|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 season ===\nGreen set new career highs in [[2013 NFL season|2013]] for receptions (98) and receiving yards (1,426, which was the second highest total in Bengals history), while also scoring 11 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00/gamelog/2013/ |title=A.J. Green 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He had six 100-yard games, including a franchise record five consecutive from Week 6 to Week 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/a.j.green/2495450/gamelogs|title=A.J. Green: Game Logs at NFL.com|website=www.nfl.com}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014 season ===\n[[File:A.J. Green vs. Browns 2014.jpg | thumb | 220x124px | right|Green warming up in [[FirstEnergy Stadium|Cleveland]] in 2014]]\nGreen caught six passes for 131 yards, including a 77-yard touchdown reception, in the Bengals 23-16 win over the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] on opening day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070rav.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Baltimore Ravens - September 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> In Week 2, he suffered a game-ending toe injury on the Bengals opening drive against the [[2014 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], resulting in Green's first career NFL game without a reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140cin.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at Cincinnati Bengals - September 14th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He returned the following week against the [[2014 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] to record six receptions for 102 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409210cin.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Cincinnati Bengals - September 21st, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> In Week 5, he aggravated his lingering toe injury and missed the following three games. In Week 14, he exploded for 224 yards on 11 receptions (a 20.4 average) and one touchdown against the [[2014 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412070cin.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Cincinnati Bengals - December 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite missing three games and nearly all of two more, Green still recorded his 4th consecutive 1,000 yard season, finishing the year with 69 receptions for 1,041 yards and 6 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00/gamelog/2014/ |title=A.J. Green 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> However, his injuries ultimately forced him to miss the postseason for the first time in his career.\n\n=== 2015 season ===\nIn Week 3 of the 2015 season, Green caught 10 passes for a career-high 227 yards and two fourth quarter touchdowns in a win over the [[2015 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270rav.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Baltimore Ravens - September 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> His 227 yards was the second highest single game total in franchise history. He finished the 2015 season with 86 receptions, 1,297 yards, and 10 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00/gamelog/2015/ |title=A.J. Green 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 18, Cincinnati Bengals 16|Wild Card Round]] against the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Steelers]], he caught five passes for 71 yards and his first postseason touchdown reception. However, a late penalty by the Bengals loomed large, yielding elimination as the Bengals lost 16\u201318.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601090cin.htm |title=Wild Card - Pittsburgh Steelers at Cincinnati Bengals - January 9th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He earned his fifth straight Pro Bowl and was ranked 16th on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000671912/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-16-A-J-Green|title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 16 A.J. Green|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 season ===\nIn the Bengals' season opener against the [[2016 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Green had 180 receiving yards, including a 54-yard touchdown as the Bengals won by a score of 23\u201322.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110nyj.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at New York Jets - September 11th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> On September 29, 2016, he caught 10 passes for 173 receiving yards and a touchdown during a 22\u20137 victory over the [[2016 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609290cin.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at Cincinnati Bengals - September 29th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> On October 23, 2016, the Bengals defeated the [[2016 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], with Green finishing the win with eight receptions for 169 receiving yards and a 48-yard touchdown reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610230cin.htm |title=Cleveland Browns at Cincinnati Bengals - October 23rd, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> The following game, Green finished with 9 catches for 121 receiving yards in a 27\u201327 tie with the [[2016 Washington Redskins|Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610300cin.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Cincinnati Bengals - October 30th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> Green returned in Week 10 and caught 7 passes for 68 receiving yards and a touchdown during the Bengals' 21\u201320 loss at the New York Giants.<ref name=\"NFLstats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/a.j.green/2495450/profile|title=NFL Player Profile:A.J. Green|access-date=November 21, 2016|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2016, Green sustained a tear to his hamstring in the first quarter of a Week 11 16\u201312 loss to the [[2016 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]]. He was inactive for the next five games before being placed on injured reserve prior to the regular-season finale.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000742429/article/aj-green-suffers-tear-in-hamstring-in-bengals-loss |title=A.J Green suffers tear in hamstring in Bengal's loss |last=Orr |first=Conor |date=November 20, 2016 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Green goes on IR to make room for extra O-lineman|url=https://www.bengals.com/news/green-goes-on-ir-to-make-room-for-extra-o-lineman-18366244|author=Hobson, Geoff|website=Bengals.com|date=December 31, 2016}}</ref> He finished the season with 66 receptions, 964 receiving yards, and 4 touchdown receptions in ten games and ten starts. The 2016 season was Green's first in the NFL without over 1,000 yards receiving, coming up just 36 yards shy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00/gamelog/2016/ |title=A.J. Green 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> Despite the injury, Green was named to his sixth straight Pro Bowl on December 20, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2017 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000760503/article/nfl-announces-2017-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> He was also ranked 17th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000816415/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-17-A-J-Green|title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 17 A.J. Green|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season===\nDuring Week 5 against the [[2017 Buffalo Bills|Buffalo Bills]], Green had two passes deflected off his hands that were intercepted and he lost a fumble, but still had an impressive outing with 189 receiving yards as the Bengals won 20\u201316.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710080cin.htm |title=Buffalo Bills at Cincinnati Bengals - October 8th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> During Week 9 against the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Green got into a fight with [[Jalen Ramsey]], resulting in both players being ejected and his first ever foul.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000871979/article/aj-green-jalen-ramsey-ejected-after-altercation |title=A.J. Green, Jalen Ramsey ejected after fight |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=November 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=A.J. Green, Jalen Ramsey will not be suspended|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000873414/article/aj-green-jalen-ramsey-will-not-be-suspended|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref> On November 9, Green was fined $42,541.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patra|first1=Kevin|title=A.J. Green won't appeal $42K fine for Week 9 scuffle|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000874379/article/aj-green-wont-appeal-42k-fine-for-week-9-scuffle|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In Week 10 against the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], he recorded 115 receiving yards and a touchdown as the Bengals lost 24\u201320.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201711120oti.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Tennessee Titans - November 12th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> On December 19, 2017, Green was named to his seventh straight Pro Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2017 season with 75 receptions for 1,078 receiving yards and eight touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00/gamelog/2017/ |title=A.J. Green 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 22nd by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000936767/Top-100-Players-of-2018-A-J-Green-No-22 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': Cincinnati Bengals wide receiver A.J. Green |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 season ===\nOn September 13, 2018, Green had the first three-touchdown game of his professional career against the [[2018 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], completing the hat trick all in the first half, with each of his first three catches resulting in touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cincyjungle.com/2018/9/14/17858342/a-j-green-reintroduces-himself-to-the-nfl-with-3-touchdowns-in-primetime|title=A.J. Green reintroduces himself to the NFL with 3 touchdowns in primetime|last=Judis|first=Patrick|date=September 14, 2018|work=Cincy Jungle}}</ref>  On October 7 in a win over the [[2018 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Green caught six passes for 112 yards, setting a franchise record with his 32nd 100-yard receiving game.<ref>{{cite web|title=A.J. Green makes history with most 100-yard games for Bengals|url=https://www.cincyjungle.com/2018/10/7/17948734/aj-green-makes-history-most-100-yard-games-for-bengals|website=CincyJungle.com|date=October 7, 2018}}</ref> He suffered a toe injury in Week 8 and missed the next three games. He returned in Week 13, however re-injured the toe and was placed on season-ending injured reserve on December 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bengals place WR A.J. Green on IR, activate CB Davontae Harris|url=https://www.cincyjungle.com/2018/12/5/18127281/bengals-place-wr-a-j-green-on-ir-activate-cb-davontae-harris|website=CincyJungle.com|date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> He finished the 2018 season with 46 receptions for 694 receiving yards and six receiving touchdowns, ending his Pro Bowl streak at seven seasons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeA.00.htm |title=A.J. Green 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season===\nDuring training camp, Green suffered torn ligaments in his ankle and was initially expected to miss the start of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2847393-aj-green-out-6-8-weeks-after-ankle-injury-diagnosed-as-torn-ligaments |title=A.J. Green out 6-8 Weeks After Ankle Injury Diagnosed as Torn Ligaments |last=Armstrong |first=Megan |date=July 28, 2019 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Despite expected to only miss a handful of games, Green missed the entire season, being inactive for every game before being placed on injured reserve on December 23, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bengals.com/news/bengals-acquire-sharif-finch-on-waivers-place-a-j-green-on-reserve-injured |title=Bengals Acquire Sharif Finch On Waivers, Place A.J. Green On Reserve/Injured |date=December 23, 2019 |website=Bengals.com |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n===2020 season===\nOn March 16, 2020, the Bengals placed the franchise tag on Green.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bengals to place tag on star wideout A.J. Green|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106338/article/bengals-to-place-tag-on-star-wideout-aj-green|author=Patra, Kevin|website=NFL.com|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"16\"| '''Regular season'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving\n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2011 NFL season|2011]] !! [[2011 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 15 || 15 || 65 || 1,057 || '''16.3''' || 58 || 7 || '''5''' || '''53''' || '''10.6''' || '''22''' || 0 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2012 NFL season|2012]] !! [[2012 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 97 || 1,350 || 13.9 || 73 || '''11''' || 4 || 38 || 9.5 || 20 || 0 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || '''98''' || '''1,426''' || 14.6  || '''82''' || 11 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! [[2014 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 13 || 13 || 69 || 1,041 || 15.1  || 82 || 6 || 2 || 2 || 1.0 || 5 || 0 || 3 || 2\n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] !! [[2015 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 86 || 1,297 || 15.1  || 80 || 10 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 10 || 10 || 66 || 964 || 14.6 || 54 || 4 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 16 || 16 || 75 || 1,078 || 14.8 || 77T || 8 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 2 || 2\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n| 9 || 9 || 46 || 694 || 15.1 || 38T || 6 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 2 || 1\n|-\n|-align=center\n ! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 Cincinnati Bengals season|CIN]]\n | colspan=\"19\"| ''Did not play''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career || 111 || 111 || 602 || 8,90