{"title_page": "Centennial Park Stadium", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Centennial Stadium}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox stadium  |\n  stadium_name  = Centennial Park Stadium |\n  image      = Tlynxstadium.jpg |\n  fullname   = Centennial Park Stadium |\n  location   = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada |\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n  nickname   = Centennial Stadium |\n  built      = 1975 |\n  opened     = 1975 |\n  owner      = [[Toronto|City of Toronto]] |\n  operator   = [[Toronto Parks, Forestry and Recreation Division|Toronto Parks, Forestry & Recreation]] |\n  surface    = [[Artificial Turf]] |\n  seating_capacity   = 2,200  |\n  scoreboard = Yes |\n  tenants    = [[Serbian White Eagles FC|Serbian White Eagles]] (1975\u20131980, 2006\u2013present)<br>[[FC Ukraine United]] (2006\u2013present)<br>[[Etobicoke Eagles]] (2009\u2013present)<br>[[Toronto Supra Portuguese]] (2001\u20132007)<br>[[Toronto Lynx]] (2002\u20132017)<br>[[Toronto Lady Lynx]] (1997\u20132015)<br>[[Toronto Atomic FC]] (2015\u20132017)<br> | \n  dimensions  =  |\n  coordinates = {{Coord|43|39|13|N|79|35|04|W|region:CA-ON_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}|\n}}\n\nThe '''Centennial Park Stadium''' is a 2,200 seat capacity [[stadium]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is primarily used for [[association football|soccer]], [[track and field]], [[Canadian football|football]] and occasionally for [[kabaddi]]. The park is also used for the [[Region of Peel Secondary Schools Athletic Association|ROPSSAA]] football finals and the PSAA (Private Schools Athletic Association) on the first Monday of May for an annual Track and Field Meet.\n\nThe stadium is named for the city park it is located in, which opened during Canada's centennial year of 1967; the stadium was opened in 1975, eight years after the centennial.\n\nIt is located within [[Centennial Park (Toronto)]] in the [[Etobicoke]] district, just south of [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] and near the intersection of Rathburn Road and Renforth Drive. It was built in 1975. The stadium hosted the [[1975 World Association of Veteran Athletes Championships|first edition of Veteran Athletes Championships]] in 1975<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shaggysphotos.com/WMA-Events/1975-WMA-News-Archives/|title=1975 WMA News Archives|last=|first=|date=|website=www.shaggysphotos.com|publisher=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> as well. \n\nThe stadium hosted the closing ceremony of the [[1976 Summer Paralympics]] and some of the sporting events.\n\nThe stadium has seating in a grandstand on the west side and a small scoreboard on the north end of the field.\n\nThe stadium is home to the [[Toronto Lynx]] soccer clubs (men's and ladies'). It hosts the Relay For Life in Toronto West event each June, a fundraiser for the Canadian Cancer Society. The stadium hosted the [[CSL Championship|CPSL/CSL Championship]] finals in 1998, 2010, 2011, and 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/98cpsl38.htm|title=Voyageurs Soccer Talk|last=Glover|first=Robin|date=|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports/10csl173.htm|title=October 30, 2010 CSL--Final preview (from CSL website)|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports11/11csl193.htm|title=October 26, 2011 CSL--preview of CSL Final (from CSL website)|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports12/12csl151.htm|title=October 25, 2012 CSL--pregame article on CSL Final (from CSL website)|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, there were calls and support for the stadium to be renamed after former Mayor [[Rob Ford]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/etobicoke-stadium-rob-ford-1.4311032|title=Toronto mayor backs renaming stadium after Rob Ford|publisher=}}</ref> as ''Rob Ford Memorial Stadium'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2017/09/28/rob-ford-memorial-stadium-proposal-triggers-gratitude-groans-in-toronto.html|title='Rob Ford Memorial Stadium' proposal triggers groans, gratitude|first=David|last=Rider|date=28 September 2017|publisher=|via=Toronto Star}}</ref> but a city council meeting voted down the motion on October 4, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2017/10/04/no-rob-ford-memorial-stadium-in-toronto-after-council-rejects-renaming-proposal.html|title=No \u2018Rob Ford Memorial Stadium\u2019 in Toronto after council rejects renaming proposal {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==See also==\n\nA list of sports stadiums located in Toronto:\n\n* [[Birchmount Stadium]] - City of Toronto / Toronto District School Board\n* [[Varsity Stadium]] - University of Toronto\n* [[Esther Shiner Stadium]] - City of Toronto\n* [[Lamport Stadium]] - City of Toronto\n* [[Monarch Park Stadium]] - Toronto District School Board\n* [[Metro Toronto Track and Field Centre]] - City of Toronto\n* [[Rosedale Field]] - City of Toronto\n* [[York Lions Stadium]] - York University\n\n{{Sport venues in Toronto}}\n{{Toronto Lynx}}\n{{Serbian White Eagles FC}}\n\n[[Category:Soccer venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Etobicoke]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Toronto Lynx]]\n[[Category:Toronto Croatia]]\n[[Category:Kabaddi venues]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1975]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Centennial Stadium}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox stadium  |\n  stadium_name  = Centennial Park Stadium |\n  image      = Tlynxstadium.jpg |\n  fullname   = Centennial Park Stadium |\n  location   = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada |\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n  nickname   = Centennial Stadium |\n  built      = 1975 |\n  opened     = 1975 |\n  owner      = [[Toronto|City of Toronto]] |\n  operator   = [[Toronto Parks, Forestry and Recreation Division|Toronto Parks, Forestry & Recreation]] |\n  surface    = [[Artificial Turf]] |\n  seating_capacity   = 2,200  |\n  scoreboard = Yes |\n  tenants    = [[Serbian White Eagles FC|Serbian White Eagles]] (1975\u20131980, 2006\u2013present)<br>[[FC Ukraine United]] (2006\u2013present)<br>[[Etobicoke Eagles]] (2009\u2013present)<br>[[Toronto Supra Portuguese]] (2001\u20132007)<br>[[Toronto Lynx]] (2002\u20132017)<br>[[Toronto Lady Lynx]] (1997\u20132015)<br>[[Toronto Atomic FC]] (2015\u20132017)<br> | \n  dimensions  =  |\n  coordinates = {{Coord|43|39|13|N|79|35|04|W|region:CA-ON_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}|\n}}\n\nThe '''Centennial Park Stadium''' is a 2,200 seat capacity [[stadium]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is primarily used for [[association football|soccer]], [[track and field]], [[Canadian football|football]] and occasionally for [[kabaddi]]. The park is also used for the [[Region of Peel Secondary Schools Athletic Association|ROPSSAA]] football finals and the PSAA (Private Schools Athletic Association) on the first Monday of May for an annual Track and Field Meet.\n\nThe stadium is named for the city park it is located in, which opened during Canada's centennial year of 1967; the stadium was opened in 1975, eight years after the centennial.\n\nIt is located within [[Centennial Park (Toronto)]] in the [[Etobicoke]] district, just south of [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] and near the intersection of Rathburn Road and Renforth Drive. It was built in 1975. The stadium hosted the [[1975 World Association of Veteran Athletes Championships|first edition of Veteran Athletes Championships]] in 1975<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shaggysphotos.com/WMA-Events/1975-WMA-News-Archives/|title=1975 WMA News Archives|last=|first=|date=|website=www.shaggysphotos.com|publisher=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> as well \n\nThe stadium hosted the closing ceremony of [[1976 Summer Paralympics]] and some of the sporting events.\n\nThe stadium has seating in a grandstand on the west side and small scoreboard on the north end of the field.\n\nThe stadium is home to the [[Toronto Lynx]] soccer clubs (men's and ladies'). It hosts the Relay For Life in Toronto West event each June, a fundraiser for the Canadian Cancer Society. The stadium hosted the [[CSL Championship|CPSL/CSL Championship]] finals in 1998, 2010, 2011, and 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/98cpsl38.htm|title=Voyageurs Soccer Talk|last=Glover|first=Robin|date=|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports/10csl173.htm|title=October 30, 2010 CSL--Final preview (from CSL website)|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports11/11csl193.htm|title=October 26, 2011 CSL--preview of CSL Final (from CSL website)|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports12/12csl151.htm|title=October 25, 2012 CSL--pregame article on CSL Final (from CSL website)|website=www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 there were calls and support for the stadium to be renamed after former Mayor [[Rob Ford]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/etobicoke-stadium-rob-ford-1.4311032|title=Toronto mayor backs renaming stadium after Rob Ford|publisher=}}</ref> as ''Rob Ford Memorial Stadium'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2017/09/28/rob-ford-memorial-stadium-proposal-triggers-gratitude-groans-in-toronto.html|title='Rob Ford Memorial Stadium' proposal triggers groans, gratitude|first=David|last=Rider|date=28 September 2017|publisher=|via=Toronto Star}}</ref> but a city council meeting voted down the motion on October 4, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2017/10/04/no-rob-ford-memorial-stadium-in-toronto-after-council-rejects-renaming-proposal.html|title=No \u2018Rob Ford Memorial Stadium\u2019 in Toronto after council rejects renaming proposal {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-10-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==See also==\n\nA list of sports stadiums located in Toronto:\n\n* [[Birchmount Stadium]] - City of Toronto / Toronto District School Board\n* [[Varsity Stadium]] - University of Toronto\n* [[Esther Shiner Stadium]] - City of Toronto\n* [[Lamport Stadium]] - City of Toronto\n* [[Monarch Park Stadium]] - Toronto District School Board\n* [[Metro Toronto Track and Field Centre]] - City of Toronto\n* [[Rosedale Field]] - City of Toronto\n* [[York Lions Stadium]] - York University\n\n{{Sport venues in Toronto}}\n{{Toronto Lynx}}\n{{Serbian White Eagles FC}}\n\n[[Category:Soccer venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Etobicoke]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Toronto Lynx]]\n[[Category:Toronto Croatia]]\n[[Category:Kabaddi venues]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1975]]\n", "name_user": "Serbianboy87", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centennial_Park_Stadium"}
{"title_page": "Judith Bernstein", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Judith Bernstein\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Judith Bernstein Portrait (1973)\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1942|10|14}}\n| birth_place      = Newark, New Jersey\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nationality      = American\n| spouse           = \n| field            = \n| training         = \n| alma_mater       = \n| movement         = \n| works            = \n| patrons          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| bgcolour         = #BCD4E6\n| education        = Yale University, Pennsylvania State University\n}}\n'''Judith Bernstein''' (born October 14, 1942) is a New York artist best known for her phallic drawings and paintings.<ref name=\"space\">{{cite book|last=Broude|first=Norma|title=Claiming Space: Some American Feminist Originators|year=2007|publisher=The Katzen American University Museum College of Art and Science|location=Washington, DC.|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Bernstein uses her art as a vehicle for her outspoken feminist and anti-war activism, provocatively drawing psychological links between the two. Her best-known work features her iconic motif of an anthropomorphized screw, which has become the basis for a number of allegories and visual puns.<ref>https://www.artsy.net/artist/judith-bernstein</ref> During the beginning of the [[Feminist art movement in the United States|Feminist Art Movement]], Bernstein was a founding member of the all-women's cooperative [[A.I.R. Gallery]] in New York.\n\nBernstein spent many years teaching in the School of Art+Design at [[State University of New York at Purchase|SUNY Purchase College]], where she is [https://www.purchase.edu/live/profiles/370-judith-bernstein Professor Emerita]. Her classes there focused on \"outrageous, outscale\" drawing, as well as drawing the figure. After retiring from SUNY Purchase, she experienced a rediscovery late in her career, as highlighted in her New York Magazine\u2019s 2015 profile titled \u201cJudith Bernstein, an art star at last at 72.\u201d<ref name=\"vulture1\">{{cite web|author=What to Stream Now |url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/05/judith-bernstein-isnt-afraid-of-dirty-words.html |title=Judith Bernstein is An Art Star at Last at 72 |publisher=Vulture |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> She has addressed the topic of her rediscovery in an interview with The New York Times, stating \u201cI call it a rebirth.\"<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/05/15/t-magazine/17older-female-artists-agnes-dene-herrera-rockbourne-farmanfarmaian.html</ref>\n\nThroughout her life, Bernstein has also been involved in the [[Guerilla Girls]], [[Art Workers' Coalition]], and Fight Censorship Group.<ref name=\"space\" /><ref name=Hard>{{cite web|title=Judith Bernstein: HARD|url=http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/judith-bernstein-hard|work=New Museum|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref> Her work is in the collection of the [[Museum of Modern Art, New York|Museum of Modern Art]], Whitney Museum of American Art, Brooklyn Museum, Jewish Museum, Carnegie Museum, Neuberger Museum, Migros Museum Z\u00fcrich, Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich, Deste Foundation for Contemporary Art, Andy Hall Foundation, Alex Katz Foundation, and Verbund Collection.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nBernstein was born into a Jewish family in [[Newark, New Jersey]] in 1942.<ref name=\"space\" /><ref name=\"censorship\">{{cite journal|last=Levin|first=Gail|title=Censorship, Politics and Sexual Imagery in the Work of Jewish-American Feminist Artists|journal=Nashim: A Journal of Jewish Women's Studies & Gender Issues|year=2007|volume=14|issue=5768|pages=63\u201396|publisher=Indiana University Press|doi=10.2979/NAS.2007.-.14.63}}</ref> Her mother was a bookkeeper and her father was a teacher.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=H. Michael|title=How to Screw Your Way to the Top: Judith Bernstein Brings Her Signature Style to the New Museum|url=http://galleristny.com/2012/10/how-to-screw-your-way-to-the-top-judith-bernstein-brings-her-signature-style-to-the-new-museum/|work=GalleristNY |publisher=Observer.com}}</ref> She learned about painting from her father who painted with his friends in their basement.<ref name=\"observer\" /> She earned her [[Master of Fine Arts]] and [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degrees from [[Yale University]].<ref name=\"observer\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Judith Bernstein: Biography|url=http://www.theboxla.com/artist.php?id=4683|work=The Box Gallery|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref> Bernstein recalls: \u201cJack Tworkov, the head of the art department, said to me on the first day, \u2018We cannot place you.\u2019 Meaning that after I left Yale, I wouldn\u2019t get a job.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|author=M.H. Miller |url=http://observer.com/2012/10/how-to-screw-your-way-to-the-top-judith-bernstein-brings-her-signature-style-to-the-new-museum/ |title=How to Screw Your Way to the Top: Judith Bernstein Brings Her Signature Style to the New Museum |publisher=Observer |date=2012-10-09 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> At that time, women were rarely placed in university positions. Prior to studying at Yale University, Bernstein received a M.Ed. and B.S. at the [[Pennsylvania State University]].\n\n== Career ==\nThroughout Bernstein\u2019s work there is playfulness within the repetition of a motif.<ref name=\"hyperallergic1\">{{cite web|url=http://hyperallergic.com/268510/history-repeating-itself-tragedy-farce-and-judith-bernstein/ |title=History Repeating Itself: Tragedy, Farce, and Judith Bernstein |publisher=Hyperallergic.com |date=2016-01-16 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> Bernstein\u2019s early drawings and paintings were influenced by both graffiti in men's bathrooms at Yale University and her view that paternalistic leadership resulted in the Vietnam War.<ref>Broude, Norma; et al. (2007). Claiming Space: Some American Feminist Originators. Washington, DC.: The Katzen American University Museum College of Art and Science.</ref> She became fascinated with graffiti after reading an article in The New York Times in the \u201860s about Edward Albee taking the title Who\u2019s Afraid of Virginia Woolf from bathroom graffiti.<ref name=\"flashartonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flashartonline.com/2014/05/traveling-into-the-void-judith-bernstein-on-art-politics-and-the-birth-of-the-universe/ |title=Judith Bernstein on Art, Politics, and the Birth of the Universe &#124; Flash Art |publisher=Flashartonline.com |date=2014-05-09 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> In discussing these images, Bernstein has stated: \u201cI realized that graffiti has psychological depth because when someone\u2019s alone and releasing on the toilet, they\u2019re also releasing from the subconscious. I began to use text like \u2018this may not be heaven but Peter hangs out here\u2019 in my drawings and paired it with crude images.\u201d<ref name=\"flashartonline1\"/> ''Fun Gun'' (1967) is a painting of an anatomical phallus shooting bullets.<ref name=\"space\" /> The same year she created the ''Union Jack-Off'' series, made with charcoal and oil stick on paper. It features two phalluses in the shape of an X within the American flag with the words \"Jack Off on U.S Policy in Vietnam.\"<ref name=\"flag\">{{cite web|title=Auction Result: Union Jack Off Flag by Judith Bernstein|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/judith-bernstein/union-jack-off-flag-rsBbv_FZfNmv-4tGvWhoVQ2|publisher=Artnet Worldwide Corporation|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBernstein\u2019s most well-known artworks are her subsequent series of biomorphic screw drawings, which she began in 1969. These monumental pieces provocatively appropriate the image of the screw as a phallic symbol of oppression\u2014as in the expression \u201cbeing screwed\u201d\u2014and evoke ominous power. One of these works, ''Horizontal'' (1973), was censored from the exhibition \u201cFocus: Women\u2019s Work\u2014 American Art in 1974\u201d at the Museum of the Philadelphia Civic Center for \u201clacking redeeming social value,\u201d phraseology commonly applied to pornography. At the time, a petition letter was issued in protest, signed by many significant artists, critics, and curators, including Clement Greenberg, Linda Nochlin, Lucy Lippard, Louise Bourgeois, and the New Museum\u2019s Founding Director, Marcia Tucker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/judith-bernstein-hard |title=Judith Bernstein: HARD |publisher=New Museum |date=2013-01-18 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref>\n\nBernstein is an active feminist and founding member of the women\u2019s cooperative [[A.I.R. Gallery]] in New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/judith-bernstein/|title=Judith Bernstein|last=Rosenmeyer|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[A.I.R. Gallery]] gave Bernstein the first solo exhibition slot in 1973.<ref name=\"observer\" /> In 1975 Bernstein was a panelist for a radio program about women \"erotic\" artists for WBAI-New York, where she discussed her experiences creating and showing her work.<ref>{{Citation|last=Judith Vivell|first=Producer|title=Erotic art by women / produced by Judith Vivell.|url=https://archive.org/details/pacifica_radio_archives-BC2255|language=English|accessdate=2017-03-11}}</ref> From 1981 to 1984 Bernstein created charcoal drawings of Venus in sexualized shapes, the series was called ''Anthurium Thru Venus''.<ref name=\"censorship\" /> She continued to make art of phalluses, and in 1993 she created a painting called ''The Dance'' of large dancing phalluses referencing Matisse's ''Dance''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth A. Sackler Center for Feminist Art: Feminist Art Base: Judith Bernstein|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/feminist_art_base/gallery/JUDITH_BERNSTEIN.php?i=620|publisher=Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBecause of pervasive sexism in the art industry, it was difficult to land exhibition engagements, and Bernstein had a hard time gaining recognition for her artwork until the 21st Century.<ref name=\"observer\" /> Some of her solo exhibitions include: ''Judith Bernstein'' at The Mitchell Algus Gallery in New York (2008), ''Signature Piece'' at Alex Zachary in New York (2010), four solo exhibitions at The Box LA (2009 - 2017), ''Birth of the Universe'' under blacklight at Gavin Brown's Enterprise in New York (2014), ''Judith Bernstein'' at Karma International in Z\u00fcrich (2014), and ''Voyeur'' at Mary Boone Gallery in New York (2015), which featured her ''Birth of the Universe'' series. In this exhibition, female genitalia filled the canvas, Bernstein employed an in-your-face and direct approach. Fluorescent color and rich oil paint portrayed the chaos and nuclear explosion that is the Big Bang with rage and the expanding universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christies.com/sales/post-war-contemporary-art-london-sept-2013/judith-bernstein.aspx |title=Interview with Judith Bernstein &#124; Post-War and Contemporary Art &#124; London &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hyperallergic.com/118770/probing-the-unknowable-judith-bernsteins-black-light-paintings/ |title=Probing the Unknowable: Judith Bernstein\u2019s Black Light Paintings |publisher=Hyperallergic.com |date=2014-04-05 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 24, 2013 |author=Sharon Mizota |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/24/entertainment/la-et-cm-review-judith-bernstein-at-the-box-20130916 |title=Review: Judith Bernstein's 'Birth of the Universe' a potent force - latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/31/arts/design/review-judith-bernstein-weaves-feminist-messages.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=By KEN JOHNSONDEC. 20, 2012 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/21/arts/design/judith-bernstein-hard-at-the-new-museum.html |title=\u2018Judith Bernstein: HARD\u2019 at the New Museum - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2012-12-20 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> She has been included in numerous group exhibitions, including: ''The Comfort of Strangers'' at MoMA PS1 (2010), ''The Last Newspaper'' at the New Museum (2010), ''The Historical Box'' at Hauser & Wirth (Z\u00fcrich in 2011 and London in 2012), ''Keep Your Timber Limber'' at ICA London (2013), and ''Toys Redux'' at Migros Museum in Z\u00fcrich (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.migrosmuseum.ch/en/events/eventdetails/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=729 |title=Migros Museum f\u00fcr Gegenwartskunst\u2013Eventdetails Artist's talk with Judith Bernstein |publisher=Migrosmuseum.ch |date=2015-06-13 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> In 2012, the New Museum was the first museum to give Bernstein a solo exhibition. It was mini-retrospective titled ''Judith Bernstein: Hard'', in which Bernstein scrawled her name on a glass wall from floor to ceiling. \u201cIt\u2019s about ego, male posturing, and also my own ego,\u201d she told New York Magazine.<ref name=\"vulture1\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Bernstein had two solo shows; ''Dicks of Death'' at Mary Boone Gallery in New York City and ''Rising'' at the Kunsthall Stavanger in Norway, along with the launch of her artist catalogue, ''Judith Bernstein Rising'' (Mousse Publishing).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moussepublishing.com/products-page/product/judith-bernstein-rising/ |title=Judith Bernstein: Rising |publisher=Mousse Publishing |date=2015-11-13 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> Both of her 2016 solo exhibitions received critical acclaim.<ref name=\"hyperallergic1\"/><ref name=\"artobserved1\">{{cite web|url=http://artobserved.com/2016/02/new-york-judith-bernstein-dicks-of-death-at-mary-boone-gallery-through-february-27th-2016/ |title=\u00bb New York \u2013 Judith Bernstein: \u201cDicks of Death\u201d at Mary Boone Gallery Through February 27th, 2016 - AO Art Observed\u2122 |publisher=Artobserved.com |date=2016-02-15 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://purple.fr/diary/judith-bernstein-dicks-of-death-exhibition-at-mary-boone-gallery-new-york/ |title=Judith Bernstein \"Dicks of Death\" exhibition at Mary Boone Gallery, New York - purple ART |publisher=Purple.fr |date=2016-01-12 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> In a review of ''Dicks of Death'', Art Observed stated: \u201cThe exhibition has a unique focus on delivering Bernstein\u2019s new body of work alongside a selection of historic pieces from the \u201860s and \u201870s, when politics related to the civilian body were making headlines, especially in relation to the protests over the Vietnam War and the resultant force expended on the populace.  Viewing Bernstein\u2019s large-scale paintings, one finds it challenging to distinguish between her older and current works, both in style and content.  Signifying the artist\u2019s decades of resilient and enduring practice, this note additionally affirms how little progression has been made regarding the issues Bernstein has been tackling, even if the scenes and players have changed.\u201d<ref name=\"artobserved1\"/> She also launched her first artist book titled ''Dicks of Death'' in collaboration with Edition Patrick Frey and received the prestigious John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship for Fine Arts in 2016 .<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.editionpatrickfrey.com/en/books/dicks-death-judith-bernstein |title=Judith Bernstein - Dicks of Death |publisher=Edition Patrick Frey |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/judith-bernstein/ |title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation &#124; Judith Bernstein |publisher=Gf.org |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref>\n\nShe lives and works in New York City.<ref name=\"observer\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Feminist art movement in the United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernstein, Judith}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Judith Bernstein\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Judith Bernstein Portrait (1973)\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1942|10|14}}\n| birth_place      = Newark, New Jersey\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nationality      = American\n| spouse           = \n| field            = \n| training         = \n| alma_mater       = \n| movement         = \n| works            = \n| patrons          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| bgcolour         = #BCD4E6\n}}\n'''Judith Bernstein''' (born October 14, 1942) is a New York artist best known for her phallic drawings and paintings.<ref name=\"space\">{{cite book|last=Broude|first=Norma|title=Claiming Space: Some American Feminist Originators|year=2007|publisher=The Katzen American University Museum College of Art and Science|location=Washington, DC.|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Bernstein uses her art as a vehicle for her outspoken feminist and anti-war activism, provocatively drawing psychological links between the two. Her best-known work features her iconic motif of an anthropomorphized screw, which has become the basis for a number of allegories and visual puns.<ref>https://www.artsy.net/artist/judith-bernstein</ref> During the beginning of the [[Feminist art movement in the United States|Feminist Art Movement]], Bernstein was a founding member of the all-women's cooperative [[A.I.R. Gallery]] in New York.\n\nBernstein spent many years teaching in the School of Art+Design at [[State University of New York at Purchase|SUNY Purchase College]], where she is [https://www.purchase.edu/live/profiles/370-judith-bernstein Professor Emerita]. Her classes there focused on \"outrageous, outscale\" drawing, as well as drawing the figure. After retiring from SUNY Purchase, she experienced a rediscovery late in her career, as highlighted in her New York Magazine\u2019s 2015 profile titled \u201cJudith Bernstein, an art star at last at 72.\u201d<ref name=\"vulture1\">{{cite web|author=What to Stream Now |url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/05/judith-bernstein-isnt-afraid-of-dirty-words.html |title=Judith Bernstein is An Art Star at Last at 72 |publisher=Vulture |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> She has addressed the topic of her rediscovery in an interview with The New York Times, stating \u201cI call it a rebirth.\"<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/05/15/t-magazine/17older-female-artists-agnes-dene-herrera-rockbourne-farmanfarmaian.html</ref>\n\nThroughout her life, Bernstein has also been involved in the [[Guerilla Girls]], [[Art Workers' Coalition]], and Fight Censorship Group.<ref name=\"space\" /><ref name=Hard>{{cite web|title=Judith Bernstein: HARD|url=http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/judith-bernstein-hard|work=New Museum|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref> Her work is in the collection of the [[Museum of Modern Art, New York|Museum of Modern Art]], Whitney Museum of American Art, Brooklyn Museum, Jewish Museum, Carnegie Museum, Neuberger Museum, Migros Museum Z\u00fcrich, Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich, Deste Foundation for Contemporary Art, Andy Hall Foundation, Alex Katz Foundation, and Verbund Collection.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nBernstein was born into a Jewish family in [[Newark, New Jersey]] in 1942.<ref name=\"space\" /><ref name=\"censorship\">{{cite journal|last=Levin|first=Gail|title=Censorship, Politics and Sexual Imagery in the Work of Jewish-American Feminist Artists|journal=Nashim: A Journal of Jewish Women's Studies & Gender Issues|year=2007|volume=14|issue=5768|pages=63\u201396|publisher=Indiana University Press|doi=10.2979/NAS.2007.-.14.63}}</ref> Her mother was a bookkeeper and her father was a teacher.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=H. Michael|title=How to Screw Your Way to the Top: Judith Bernstein Brings Her Signature Style to the New Museum|url=http://galleristny.com/2012/10/how-to-screw-your-way-to-the-top-judith-bernstein-brings-her-signature-style-to-the-new-museum/|work=GalleristNY |publisher=Observer.com}}</ref> She learned about painting from her father who painted with his friends in their basement.<ref name=\"observer\" /> She earned her [[Master of Fine Arts]] and [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degrees from [[Yale University]].<ref name=\"observer\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Judith Bernstein: Biography|url=http://www.theboxla.com/artist.php?id=4683|work=The Box Gallery|accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref> Bernstein recalls: \u201cJack Tworkov, the head of the art department, said to me on the first day, \u2018We cannot place you.\u2019 Meaning that after I left Yale, I wouldn\u2019t get a job.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|author=M.H. Miller |url=http://observer.com/2012/10/how-to-screw-your-way-to-the-top-judith-bernstein-brings-her-signature-style-to-the-new-museum/ |title=How to Screw Your Way to the Top: Judith Bernstein Brings Her Signature Style to the New Museum |publisher=Observer |date=2012-10-09 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> At that time, women were rarely placed in university positions. Prior to studying at Yale University, Bernstein received a M.Ed. and B.S. at the [[Pennsylvania State University]].\n\n== Career ==\nThroughout Bernstein\u2019s work there is playfulness within the repetition of a motif.<ref name=\"hyperallergic1\">{{cite web|url=http://hyperallergic.com/268510/history-repeating-itself-tragedy-farce-and-judith-bernstein/ |title=History Repeating Itself: Tragedy, Farce, and Judith Bernstein |publisher=Hyperallergic.com |date=2016-01-16 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> Bernstein\u2019s early drawings and paintings were influenced by both graffiti in men's bathrooms at Yale University and her view that paternalistic leadership resulted in the Vietnam War.<ref>Broude, Norma; et al. (2007). Claiming Space: Some American Feminist Originators. Washington, DC.: The Katzen American University Museum College of Art and Science.</ref> She became fascinated with graffiti after reading an article in The New York Times in the \u201860s about Edward Albee taking the title Who\u2019s Afraid of Virginia Woolf from bathroom graffiti.<ref name=\"flashartonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flashartonline.com/2014/05/traveling-into-the-void-judith-bernstein-on-art-politics-and-the-birth-of-the-universe/ |title=Judith Bernstein on Art, Politics, and the Birth of the Universe &#124; Flash Art |publisher=Flashartonline.com |date=2014-05-09 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> In discussing these images, Bernstein has stated: \u201cI realized that graffiti has psychological depth because when someone\u2019s alone and releasing on the toilet, they\u2019re also releasing from the subconscious. I began to use text like \u2018this may not be heaven but Peter hangs out here\u2019 in my drawings and paired it with crude images.\u201d<ref name=\"flashartonline1\"/> ''Fun Gun'' (1967) is a painting of an anatomical phallus shooting bullets.<ref name=\"space\" /> The same year she created the ''Union Jack-Off'' series, made with charcoal and oil stick on paper. It features two phalluses in the shape of an X within the American flag with the words \"Jack Off on U.S Policy in Vietnam.\"<ref name=\"flag\">{{cite web|title=Auction Result: Union Jack Off Flag by Judith Bernstein|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/judith-bernstein/union-jack-off-flag-rsBbv_FZfNmv-4tGvWhoVQ2|publisher=Artnet Worldwide Corporation|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBernstein\u2019s most well-known artworks are her subsequent series of biomorphic screw drawings, which she began in 1969. These monumental pieces provocatively appropriate the image of the screw as a phallic symbol of oppression\u2014as in the expression \u201cbeing screwed\u201d\u2014and evoke ominous power. One of these works, ''Horizontal'' (1973), was censored from the exhibition \u201cFocus: Women\u2019s Work\u2014 American Art in 1974\u201d at the Museum of the Philadelphia Civic Center for \u201clacking redeeming social value,\u201d phraseology commonly applied to pornography. At the time, a petition letter was issued in protest, signed by many significant artists, critics, and curators, including Clement Greenberg, Linda Nochlin, Lucy Lippard, Louise Bourgeois, and the New Museum\u2019s Founding Director, Marcia Tucker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmuseum.org/exhibitions/view/judith-bernstein-hard |title=Judith Bernstein: HARD |publisher=New Museum |date=2013-01-18 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref>\n\nBernstein is an active feminist and founding member of the women\u2019s cooperative [[A.I.R. Gallery]] in New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/judith-bernstein/|title=Judith Bernstein|last=Rosenmeyer|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The [[A.I.R. Gallery]] gave Bernstein the first solo exhibition slot in 1973.<ref name=\"observer\" /> In 1975 Bernstein was a panelist for a radio program about women \"erotic\" artists for WBAI-New York, where she discussed her experiences creating and showing her work.<ref>{{Citation|last=Judith Vivell|first=Producer|title=Erotic art by women / produced by Judith Vivell.|url=https://archive.org/details/pacifica_radio_archives-BC2255|language=English|accessdate=2017-03-11}}</ref> From 1981 to 1984 Bernstein created charcoal drawings of Venus in sexualized shapes, the series was called ''Anthurium Thru Venus''.<ref name=\"censorship\" /> She continued to make art of phalluses, and in 1993 she created a painting called ''The Dance'' of large dancing phalluses referencing Matisse's ''Dance''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth A. Sackler Center for Feminist Art: Feminist Art Base: Judith Bernstein|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/feminist_art_base/gallery/JUDITH_BERNSTEIN.php?i=620|publisher=Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBecause of pervasive sexism in the art industry, it was difficult to land exhibition engagements, and Bernstein had a hard time gaining recognition for her artwork until the 21st Century.<ref name=\"observer\" /> Some of her solo exhibitions include: ''Judith Bernstein'' at The Mitchell Algus Gallery in New York (2008), ''Signature Piece'' at Alex Zachary in New York (2010), four solo exhibitions at The Box LA (2009 - 2017), ''Birth of the Universe'' under blacklight at Gavin Brown's Enterprise in New York (2014), ''Judith Bernstein'' at Karma International in Z\u00fcrich (2014), and ''Voyeur'' at Mary Boone Gallery in New York (2015), which featured her ''Birth of the Universe'' series. In this exhibition, female genitalia filled the canvas, Bernstein employed an in-your-face and direct approach. Fluorescent color and rich oil paint portrayed the chaos and nuclear explosion that is the Big Bang with rage and the expanding universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christies.com/sales/post-war-contemporary-art-london-sept-2013/judith-bernstein.aspx |title=Interview with Judith Bernstein &#124; Post-War and Contemporary Art &#124; London &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hyperallergic.com/118770/probing-the-unknowable-judith-bernsteins-black-light-paintings/ |title=Probing the Unknowable: Judith Bernstein\u2019s Black Light Paintings |publisher=Hyperallergic.com |date=2014-04-05 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=September 24, 2013 |author=Sharon Mizota |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/24/entertainment/la-et-cm-review-judith-bernstein-at-the-box-20130916 |title=Review: Judith Bernstein's 'Birth of the Universe' a potent force - latimes |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/31/arts/design/review-judith-bernstein-weaves-feminist-messages.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=By KEN JOHNSONDEC. 20, 2012 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/21/arts/design/judith-bernstein-hard-at-the-new-museum.html |title=\u2018Judith Bernstein: HARD\u2019 at the New Museum - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2012-12-20 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> She has been included in numerous group exhibitions, including: ''The Comfort of Strangers'' at MoMA PS1 (2010), ''The Last Newspaper'' at the New Museum (2010), ''The Historical Box'' at Hauser & Wirth (Z\u00fcrich in 2011 and London in 2012), ''Keep Your Timber Limber'' at ICA London (2013), and ''Toys Redux'' at Migros Museum in Z\u00fcrich (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.migrosmuseum.ch/en/events/eventdetails/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=729 |title=Migros Museum f\u00fcr Gegenwartskunst\u2013Eventdetails Artist's talk with Judith Bernstein |publisher=Migrosmuseum.ch |date=2015-06-13 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> In 2012, the New Museum was the first museum to give Bernstein a solo exhibition. It was mini-retrospective titled ''Judith Bernstein: Hard'', in which Bernstein scrawled her name on a glass wall from floor to ceiling. \u201cIt\u2019s about ego, male posturing, and also my own ego,\u201d she told New York Magazine.<ref name=\"vulture1\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Bernstein had two solo shows; ''Dicks of Death'' at Mary Boone Gallery in New York City and ''Rising'' at the Kunsthall Stavanger in Norway, along with the launch of her artist catalogue, ''Judith Bernstein Rising'' (Mousse Publishing).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moussepublishing.com/products-page/product/judith-bernstein-rising/ |title=Judith Bernstein: Rising |publisher=Mousse Publishing |date=2015-11-13 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> Both of her 2016 solo exhibitions received critical acclaim.<ref name=\"hyperallergic1\"/><ref name=\"artobserved1\">{{cite web|url=http://artobserved.com/2016/02/new-york-judith-bernstein-dicks-of-death-at-mary-boone-gallery-through-february-27th-2016/ |title=\u00bb New York \u2013 Judith Bernstein: \u201cDicks of Death\u201d at Mary Boone Gallery Through February 27th, 2016 - AO Art Observed\u2122 |publisher=Artobserved.com |date=2016-02-15 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://purple.fr/diary/judith-bernstein-dicks-of-death-exhibition-at-mary-boone-gallery-new-york/ |title=Judith Bernstein \"Dicks of Death\" exhibition at Mary Boone Gallery, New York - purple ART |publisher=Purple.fr |date=2016-01-12 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref> In a review of ''Dicks of Death'', Art Observed stated: \u201cThe exhibition has a unique focus on delivering Bernstein\u2019s new body of work alongside a selection of historic pieces from the \u201860s and \u201870s, when politics related to the civilian body were making headlines, especially in relation to the protests over the Vietnam War and the resultant force expended on the populace.  Viewing Bernstein\u2019s large-scale paintings, one finds it challenging to distinguish between her older and current works, both in style and content.  Signifying the artist\u2019s decades of resilient and enduring practice, this note additionally affirms how little progression has been made regarding the issues Bernstein has been tackling, even if the scenes and players have changed.\u201d<ref name=\"artobserved1\"/> She also launched her first artist book titled ''Dicks of Death'' in collaboration with Edition Patrick Frey and received the prestigious John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship for Fine Arts in 2016 .<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.editionpatrickfrey.com/en/books/dicks-death-judith-bernstein |title=Judith Bernstein - Dicks of Death |publisher=Edition Patrick Frey |date= |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/judith-bernstein/ |title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation &#124; Judith Bernstein |publisher=Gf.org |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref>\n\nShe lives and works in New York City.<ref name=\"observer\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Feminist art movement in the United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernstein, Judith}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from Newark, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n", "name_user": "JunPFB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Education Added Needs Links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judith_Bernstein"}
